import os
import pandas as pd
directory = './'
combined_df = pd.DataFrame()
for filename in os.listdir(directory):
    if filename.endswith(".gene_mapping_data.txt"):
        # Extract sample name from the filename
        sample_name = filename.split('.')[0].replace("output_", "")
        # Load the data from the file
        filepath = os.path.join(directory, filename)
        sample_df = pd.read_csv(filepath, sep="\t")
        sample_df['Sample'] = sample_name
        combined_df = pd.concat([combined_df, sample_df], ignore_index=True)
combined_df.to_csv('combined_gene_mapping_data.csv', index=False)

print("Combined dataset saved as 'combined_gene_mapping_data.csv'.")

Combined dataset saved as 'combined_gene_mapping_data.csv'.

import pandas as pd

input_file = 'combined_gene_mapping_data.csv'
combined_df = pd.read_csv(input_file)

min_mapped_reads = 1
min_avg_percent_coverage = 20.0

filtered_df = combined_df[
    (combined_df['All Mapped Reads'] >= min_mapped_reads) &
    (combined_df['Average Percent Coverage'] >= min_avg_percent_coverage)
]
# Save the filtered dataset to a new CSV file
output_file = 'filtered_gene_mapping_data.csv'
filtered_df.to_csv(output_file, index=False)

print(f"Filtered dataset saved as '{output_file}'.")

import pandas as pd
filtered_file = 'filtered_gene_mapping_data.csv'
filtered_df = pd.read_csv(filtered_file)
metadata_file = 'metadata_hww1_py.csv'
metadata_df = pd.read_csv(metadata_file)

metadata_cols = ['Sample_ID', 'Sample_type', 'Collection_date', 'Hospital']
metadata_subset_df = metadata_df[metadata_cols]
merged_df = pd.merge(filtered_df, metadata_subset_df, left_on='Sample', right_on='Sample_ID', how='left')

output_file = 'filtered_file_with_metadata.csv'
merged_df.to_csv(output_file, index=False)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from scipy.stats import mannwhitneyu

# Load the data
input_file = 'beta_lactamase_gene_mapping_data.csv'  # Update with the actual file path
merged_df = pd.read_csv(input_file)

# Filter the data to keep only rows with 'All Mapped Reads' values
merged_df = merged_df.dropna(subset=['All Mapped Reads'])

# Set a higher resolution for the saved figure
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# Set a custom color palette and general figure style
sns.set_palette("Set2")
sns.set_context("talk")  # Larger font sizes for better readability
sns.despine(left=True)

# Create a barplot with facet wrapping by 'Hospital'
g = sns.catplot(
    data=merged_df, 
    x='Sample_type', 
    y='All Mapped Reads', 
    col='Hospital', 
    kind='bar', 
    estimator=sum,  # Sum the values for each 'Sample_type'
    palette='Set2',  # Custom color palette
    height=6, 
    aspect=1.2,
    ci=None,  # Hide confidence intervals if unnecessary
    linewidth=1,  # Thin lines for borders
)

# Perform statistical analysis and annotate the plot
for ax, (hospital, data) in zip(g.axes.flat, merged_df.groupby('Hospital')):
    # Get the data for each 'Sample_type'
    raw_data = data[data['Sample_type'] == 'Raw']['All Mapped Reads']
    treated_data = data[data['Sample_type'] == 'Treated']['All Mapped Reads']
    
    # Perform the Mann-Whitney U test on individual sample values
    if len(raw_data) > 0 and len(treated_data) > 0:
        stat, p_value = mannwhitneyu(raw_data, treated_data, alternative='two-sided')
        # Determine the maximum y-value for setting the annotation position
        max_y = data.groupby('Sample_type')['All Mapped Reads'].sum().max()
        ax.text(
            0.5,  # x-position (centered between the bars)
            max_y + 0.1 * max_y,  # y-position (10% above the highest bar)
            f'p = {p_value:.3e}', 
            ha='center', 
            va='bottom', 
            fontsize=12,  # Adjust font size for readability
            color='red',
            weight='bold'  # Bold text for emphasis
        )

# Customize the plot
g.set_axis_labels('Sample Type', 'Total Qualified Mapped Reads')
g.set_titles('{col_name}', weight='bold')  # Make title bold
g.set_xticklabels(rotation=45)
g.set(ylim=(0, None))  # Set lower y-limit to 0 for clarity
g.fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.85)  # Adjust the top margin to avoid overlap with the title

# Add an overall title
#g.fig.suptitle('Comparison of Beta-Lactamase Gene Read Counts by Sample Type and Hospital', fontsize=16, weight='bold')

# Save the plot with a high resolution
g.savefig('beta_lactamase_mapped_reads.png', format='png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load the data
input_file = 'beta_lactamase_gene_mapping_data1.csv'
merged_df = pd.read_csv(input_file)

# Filter out rows with missing AMR Gene Family data
filtered_df = merged_df.dropna(subset=['AMR Gene Family'])

# Add a presence column (1 for presence, 0 for absence)
filtered_df['Presence'] = 1

# Create a presence-absence matrix with AMR Gene Families on y-axis
presence_absence = filtered_df.pivot_table(index='AMR Gene Family', columns=['Sample_type', 'Hospital'], values='Presence', fill_value=0)

# Set up the figure
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# Create a heatmap with AMR Gene Families on the y-axis and Sample_type on the x-axis
g = sns.heatmap(presence_absence, cmap='Blues', linewidths=0.5, linecolor='gray', cbar=True)

# Customize the plot
plt.xlabel('Sample Type and Hospital', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('AMR Gene Family', fontsize=12)
plt.title('AMR Gene Family Presence by Sample Type and Hospital', fontsize=14)

# Adjust layout
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.tight_layout()

# Save the heatmap as a PNG file
plt.savefig('AMR_Gene_Presence.png', format='png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
# Show the plot
plt.show()

# calculate relative abundance
In[190]:
# Group by 'Sample_ID' and 'Drug Class' to calculate the count of each drug class per sample
abundance_df = data.groupby(['Sample_ID', 'Drug Class']).size().reset_index(name='Count')

# Pivot the table to get Drug Classes as columns and Sample_ID as rows
abundance_pivot = abundance_df.pivot(index='Sample_ID', columns='Drug Class', values='Count').fillna(0)

# Calculate relative abundance per Sample_ID (convert to percentages)
abundance_pivot = abundance_pivot.div(abundance_pivot.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100  # Convert to percentage

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import numpy as np

# Define 7 distinct colors (the 7th one will only have a plain version)
base_colors = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c', '#d62728', '#9467bd', '#8c564b', '#17becf']
hatch_patterns = ['', '//']  # Plain and striped

# Get the drug classes from the abundance_pivot dataframe
drug_classes = abundance_pivot.columns

# Create a color and hatch mapping for each drug class
color_mapping = {}
for i, drug_class in enumerate(drug_classes):
    if drug_class == 'Other_classes':
        # The 13th class will be grey without any hatching
        color_mapping[drug_class] = {'color': 'grey', 'hatch': None}
    else:
        # Alternate between plain and striped for the first 6 colors, the 7th is plain
        color_mapping[drug_class] = {
            'color': base_colors[i % len(base_colors)],  # Cycle through 7 base colors
            'hatch': hatch_patterns[i // len(base_colors)] if i < 12 else ''  # Apply hatch for the first 12, plain for 13th
        }

# Plot the stacked bar plot with alternating hatches and colors
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 8))

# Loop through the drug classes and plot each segment with distinct colors/hatches
bars = []
for i, drug_class in enumerate(drug_classes):
    color_info = color_mapping[drug_class]
    bars.append(ax.bar(
        abundance_pivot.index,  # x-axis labels (Sample IDs)
        abundance_pivot[drug_class],  # The height of each segment (relative abundance)
        bottom=abundance_pivot.iloc[:, :i].sum(axis=1) if i > 0 else None,  # Stack bars
        color=color_info['color'],  # Color of the segment
        edgecolor='black',  # Add edge color for clarity
        hatch=color_info['hatch'],  # Apply hatching where needed
        label=drug_class  # Label for the legend
    ))

# Set plot labels and title
plt.xlabel('Sample ID')
plt.ylabel('Relative Abundance (%)')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.legend(title='Drug Class', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')

# Adjust layout to fit everything nicely
plt.tight_layout()

# Save the plot to a PNG file
plt.savefig('drug_class_relative_abundance.png', format='png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd

# Assuming 'abundance_pivot' contains relative abundance data and 'Sample_type' exists
# Define 7 distinct colors (7th one will only have plain version)
base_colors = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c', '#d62728', '#9467bd', '#8c564b', '#17becf']
hatch_patterns = ['', '//']  # Plain and striped for each color

# Get the drug classes from the abundance_pivot dataframe
drug_classes = abundance_pivot.columns

# Create a color and hatch mapping for each drug class
color_mapping = {}
for i, drug_class in enumerate(drug_classes):
    if drug_class == 'Other_classes':
        color_mapping[drug_class] = {'color': 'grey', 'hatch': None}
    else:
        color_mapping[drug_class] = {
            'color': base_colors[i % len(base_colors)],  
            'hatch': hatch_patterns[i // len(base_colors)] if i < 12 else ''  
        }

# Get unique sample types from the metadata (assuming 'Sample_type' column exists)
sample_types = merged_df['Sample_type'].unique()

# Determine the number of rows and columns based on the number of sample types
ncols = 2
nrows = int(np.ceil(len(sample_types) / ncols))

# Set up the figure with subplots in a grid layout
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows, ncols=ncols, figsize=(14, 8 * nrows))  # Adjust the overall figure size
axes = axes.flatten()  # Flatten the axes array to iterate over it easily

# Loop through each sample type and plot the data
bars = []
for ax, sample_type in zip(axes, sample_types):
    # Filter the abundance_pivot for the current sample type
    sample_indices = merged_df[merged_df['Sample_type'] == sample_type]['Sample_ID']
    filtered_abundance = abundance_pivot.loc[sample_indices]
    
    # Plot each drug class
    for i, drug_class in enumerate(drug_classes):
        color_info = color_mapping[drug_class]
        bar = ax.bar(
            filtered_abundance.index,  
            filtered_abundance[drug_class],  
            bottom=filtered_abundance.iloc[:, :i].sum(axis=1) if i > 0 else None,  
            color=color_info['color'],  
            edgecolor='black',  
            hatch=color_info['hatch'],  
            label=drug_class  # Ensure label is added to every plot
        )
        bars.append(bar)

    ax.set_title(f'{sample_type}', fontsize=14)
    ax.set_xlabel('Sample ID')
    ax.set_ylabel('Relative Abundance (%)')
    ax.set_xticklabels(filtered_abundance.index, rotation=90)

# Hide any unused subplots
for i in range(len(sample_types), len(axes)):
    fig.delaxes(axes[i])

# Add legend outside the plot for all drug classes
handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
fig.legend(handles, labels, title='Drug Class', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')

plt.tight_layout()

# Save the plot to a PNG file
plt.savefig('drug_class_RA_treatment.png', format='png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
# Show the plot
plt.show()
